        content='The research plan is well-structured and scientifically sound. To further strengthen the analysis and ensure the "minimal effective theory" goal is met, I suggest the following refinements:\n\n1. **Address the "Lévy-Lorentz" Specifics in Step 6**: Step 6 currently focuses on Sisyphus cooling and PM maps for the effective Langevin analysis. The Lévy-Lorentz gas is a crucial mechanism for understanding "geometric" Lévy flights. I suggest including it in the drift-diffusion analysis to see if it can be mapped to an effective Langevin equation with state-dependent diffusion, which is a known theoretical approach for this system.\n\n2. **Sensitivity to Lag Time ($\\tau$) in Step 3**: In the heavy-tail regime, the tail index $\\alpha$ can appear to change with the lag time $\\tau$ due to the Central Limit Theorem (for $\\alpha=2$) or the stability property (for $\\alpha<2$). I suggest explicitly checking the stability of the estimated $\\alpha$ across multiple lag times $\\tau$ to confirm that the mechanism truly converges to a stable distribution rather than just exhibiting transient heavy tails.\n\n3. **Refine the "Minimal Model" Criterion (Step 8)**: "Complexity" is often subjective. To make this more rigorous, consider incorporating the **Akaike Information Criterion (AIC)** or **Bayesian Information Criterion (BIC)** when comparing the effective Langevin models (from Step 6) against the ground truth. This provides a formal statistical penalty for the number of parameters, directly supporting the identification of the "minimal" theory.\n\n4. **Visualizing the "Lévy-ness"**: In Step 7, consider adding a visualization of the "Scaling Collapse" (e.g., plotting $t^{1/\\alpha} P(x,t)$ vs $x/t^{1/\\alpha}$ for different $t$). This is a standard and highly intuitive way to demonstrate universality and will provide a strong visual validation of the KL-divergence results.\n\n5. **Data Integrity Check**: Given that the datasets have different time-step densitie